This version is materially better. It now has a thesis, a governing framework, and an actual institutional alternative. The main improvement is that it stops free-associating and starts arguing.

The remaining weaknesses are mostly about overclaim and institutional realism.

1. The proposed split is cleaner on paper than in practice. A technical consortium that defines benchmarks, chooses what to measure, and frames comparative results still exerts major downstream power over procurement. That is not full separation; it is influence by metric design. You should say that the architecture reduces capture risk rather than solves it.

2. The CERN/LIGO analogy is not quite right. Those are scientific collaborations organized around shared research goals, not adversarial vendor evaluation under procurement pressure. That analogy flatters the model. A better comparison is standards-and-test institutions, certification labs, or clinical evidence generation separated from reimbursement decisions.

3. The transparency protocol is too absolute. “All benchmark data released under open-source licenses” will often be impossible because vendor IP, export controls, and security constraints will block full disclosure. If you leave it as written, it is easy to attack. Better: publish methodology, summary results, uncertainty bounds, and redacted interaction logs by default, with a defined confidential annex process.

4. The Procurement Advisory Office is described as if direct vendor contact is always corrupting. That is too rigid. Procurement decision-makers usually need some controlled engagement to assess manufacturability, delivery risk, support models, and industrial capacity. The stronger claim is not “no contact,” but “no joint technical development and no opaque evidentiary channels.”

5. The F-35 example is risky unless you can defend it precisely. It is vivid, but if the historical claim is even slightly contestable, it becomes a distraction. The argument does not need it. If you keep an example, use it lightly and as analogy, not proof.

6. The piece still underplays the hardest objection to your own model: speed. A three-body system may be more neutral but also slower, more bureaucratic, and easier for fast-moving vendors to game procedurally. You should address that tradeoff directly.

The best way to sharpen it further is to move from “three bodies, one protocol” to “two layers, one firewall”:

- Layer 1: a public technical evidence function that runs benchmarks, publishes methods, and maintains substrate fluency.
- Layer 2: a procurement decision function that uses that evidence plus strategic criteria.
- Firewall: disclosure rules, recusal rules, audit trails, challenge procedures, and limits on joint development.

That is simpler, more defensible, and less vulnerable to “institutional baroque” criticism.

One sentence I would change immediately is this:
“Independence is structural, not aspirational: they never co-develop anything with vendors.”

Make it:
“Independence is structural rather than merely aspirational: procurement decision-makers may receive vendor submissions and conduct formal hearings, but they do not co-develop benchmarks, verification methods, or technical claims with vendors.”

